      },
      "date": "2017-01-05 19:09:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nCan we get someone else to review? Thanks",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "c6b7c1dc2cabb83969e94207f28180003a263fcb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2017-01-05 20:00:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n\nI think a clearer explanation of the problem is needed.  Lustre can build against ZFS and other externally-built kernel modules without requiring this kind of special handling.\n\nIt sounds to me like you have an environment where the gni prerequisite hasn't been properly packaged and installed.  If it was, this problem wouldn't exist.  I would argue then that the core code should not be an enabler of broken processes.  If others want to have a weird broken process, they can carry the burden of carrying weird hacks to Lustre support that rather than making it a community burden.\n\nIf I'm missing something, please do elaborate on why the build environment is not a broken one.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "d05a3665ade36f408b18f5d681870de76049c333",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2018-03-08 22:41:18.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    }
